      Rates go up
   =20
 =20

This is maybe the first real interest-rate-hiking cycle of my professional =
life, and I=E2=80=99m kind of excited? Not just my=C2=A0professional life. =
I=E2=80=99m pretty old!
  [1]
=C2=A0A whole lot of people in fairly senior roles at a whole lot of financ=
ial services companies grew up=C2=A0a world of low interest rates; large ex=
panses of the financial industry=C2=A0collectively forgot that rates could =
go up. Now rates have gone up. Those two facts =E2=80=94=C2=A0rates have go=
ne up, and lots of people have=C2=A0never seen rates go up =E2=80=94=C2=A0a=
re going to lead to interesting results. Weird stuff will happen because th=
e most predictable fact in the world =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cinterest rates=
 can=E2=80=99t stay low forever=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0was, somehow, unfor=
eseen.
Look around! Is the story of crypto =E2=80=9Cwhen rates were zero for ages,=
 a dollar in 100 years was worth as much as a dollar now, so people got rea=
lly into trading digital assets that had no foreseeable cash flows, and the=
n rates went up and everyone woke up and realized that was dumb and stopped=
=E2=80=9D? Is that also the story of blitzscaling tech-startup unicorns? No=
, but also a little bit yes?
More concretely, is the story of the 2023 US regional banking crisis =E2=80=
=9Cwhen rates were zero forever, banks borrowed short at 0% to lend long at=
 3%, and then rates went up, their asset values collapsed and there was a r=
un on deposits, all of which was extremely foreseeable except that the bank=
s and bank regulators forgot that interest rates could go up?=E2=80=9D I me=
an,   I have argued that the actual story is   more subtle than that, that =
you need to think about things like unexpectedly high deposit betas and dec=
lining relationships and=C2=A0broader public awareness of=C2=A0bank balance=
 sheets,=C2=A0that banks reasonably expected rising rates to be=C2=A0good=
=C2=A0for them and were caught out by social and technological changes. But=
 that=C2=A0is=C2=A0kind of a straightforward explanation, no? =E2=80=9CSome=
 banks were not prepared for rising rates because they forgot that there wa=
s such a thing=E2=80=9D?=C2=A0
Or I mean =E2=80=A6=C2=A0is the story of modern private equity and leverage=
d-loan markets something like =E2=80=9Cfloating-rate debt is very cheap whe=
n rates are zero, so if you buy a bunch of companies and load them up with =
cheap floating-rate debt then you will predictably have high returns to equ=
ity and manageable interest expense,=E2=80=9D and then rates went up and th=
e whole thing broke? Do we have an economy in which a lot of businesses are=
 financed with a lot of floating-rate debt, not because that is a sensible =
way to finance their businesses in the long run, but because a lot of fairl=
y young private-equity professionals forgot that rates could go up? Ehh I d=
on=E2=80=99t know, not really, but maybe a little. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=
=A0  Silas Brown, Abhinav Ramnarayan and Paula Seligson report:

By failing to appreciate just how much central banks would jack up rates, m=
any private equity firms opted against hedging arrangements that could have=
 shielded companies saddled with $3 trillion in floating-rate debt from ris=
ing interest costs, that in some cases, doubled or more. For much of the pa=
st decade, those hedges cost next to nothing.
=E2=80=9CNot many folks were worrying about this and a lot of businesses ha=
ve been burnt really badly,=E2=80=9D said Chris Scott, Carlyle Group Inc.=
=E2=80=99s head of European capital markets.
Estimates are hotly debated and buyout firms across the industry declined t=
o talk specifics. But in the US, nearly three-quarters of the floating-rate=
 debt taken out during the leveraged-buyout boom lacked hedges as recently =
as August, according to an analysis by Bank of America. Man Group Plc resea=
rch suggests that over 70% of the total in Europe remained unhedged at the =
end of January, well after the European Central Bank began its tightening c=
ampaign.
Whatever the precise number, this much is clear: The consequences of rising=
 rates for hundreds, if not thousands, of companies could be crippling, and=
 the fallout widespread. Not only for investors, who face deep losses, or w=
orkers, who stand to lose jobs, but also the global economy, which could be=
 upended if corporate defaults pile up. =E2=80=A6
The situation is the latest example of how Wall Street=E2=80=99s best and t=
he brightest =E2=80=94 from bank executives to traders and economists =E2=
=80=94 were almost uniformly blindsided by the pickup in inflation and how =
forcefully central banks around the world would respond to tamp it down. It=
=E2=80=99s also a sharp reversal for private equity itself, which leveraged=
 a flood of central bank money to finance a record number of buyouts at roc=
k-bottom rates over the past decade. =E2=80=A6
Across North America, interest costs at the median private equity-backed co=
mpany ballooned to 43% of Ebitda last year, according to research published=
 last month by Verdad Advisers, which analyzed 350 such companies that are =
either publicly traded or have publicly traded debt. Not only is that six t=
imes as much as the median S&P 500 company, but the interest burden will ke=
ep growing this year as rates keep rising.
In fact, interest rates on the largest US leveraged loans (which simply ref=
er to junk-rated loans which are often used to finance buyouts) hit an aver=
age of 10% this month, from 3.9% at the end of 2021, just before the Federa=
l Reserve embarked on its most aggressive tightening campaign in a generati=
on, based on the Morningstar LSTA US Leveraged Loan 100 Index.

At some level =E2=80=9Cas interest rates go up, companies will have to pay =
more interest on their debt=E2=80=9D is a pretty banal finding, and yet it =
does seem to come as a surprise.

