   =20
      Two Sigma
   =20
 =20

There are two paradigmatic ways to run a hedge fund:
=09Pirate captain with a pirate crew; or=09Institutional firm with professi=
onal management, well-defined career paths and succession plans, replicable=
 processes that do not depend on the genius of the charismatic founder, etc=
.

Most hedge funds start as pirate crews, and then if they get big and succes=
sful enough the interesting question is whether they can successfully make =
the transition to being permanent institutional firms. A weirder model, tho=
ugh,=C2=A0is=C2=A0two=C2=A0charismatic pirate captains with=C2=A0two=C2=A0p=
irate crews who are=C2=A0constantly shooting at each other:

Over the last 22 years, John Overdeck and David Siegel built Two Sigma Inve=
stments into a $60 billion quant-trading behemoth. But behind the scenes, t=
he billionaire co-founders have clashed over the firm=E2=80=99s direction, =
succession planning and more, people familiar with the matter said. =C2=A0
The relationship has deteriorated to the point where Two Sigma felt the nee=
d to disclose the friction in a March 31  securities filing. In a little-no=
ticed section on =E2=80=9Cmaterial risks=E2=80=9D related to its investment=
s strategies, the firm warned that Two Sigma=E2=80=99s management committee=
=E2=80=94which includes only Overdeck and Siegel=E2=80=94is having difficul=
ty making key decisions, a disclosure that lawyers, investors and others sa=
y is virtually unprecedented in the investment world. =E2=80=A6
The executives, who have offices about 30 feet from each other, split their=
 duties. Overdeck has managed the investment researchers, or modelers, usua=
lly favoring a hands-off approach. Siegel oversees the firm=E2=80=99s engin=
eers while appearing at industry conferences, often to speak about the futu=
re of artificial intelligence, which he studied decades ago at MIT. Each ex=
ecutive has groups of loyalists within the firm.
=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s two tribes,=E2=80=9D said a person close to the firm.=
 =E2=80=A6
In recent years, Overdeck and Siegel have rarely appeared together at firm =
events. They frequently snipe at each other in meetings, attendees said. De=
cisions get delayed and projects killed because employees assume they won=
=E2=80=99t be able to get both founders to agree, the people said.=C2=A0
One person familiar with Overdeck and Siegel described their relationship a=
s evolving over the years =E2=80=9Cfrom irritation to Cold War to hot war.=
=E2=80=9D

There is another axis on which you can arrange hedge funds, though: Some he=
dge funds have essentially systematic, computer-driven, quant-y investment =
strategies, while others depend on the fundamental instincts of their portf=
olio managers (pirate captain or otherwise). Two Sigma is quite firmly in t=
he quant camp. I have a   half-joking model for Bridgewater Associates, ano=
ther quant-y firm, in which:
=09The computer makes the investment decisions,=09Freeing up the employees =
to engage in a lot of bizarre interpersonal drama,=09Which in turn distract=
s=C2=A0them from interfering in the investing decisions, allowing the compu=
ter to just get down to work with perfect rationality and no distractions.

Something like that seems to be happening at Two Sigma, which is apparently=
 paralyzed with interpersonal drama and yet keeps investing just fine:
Some senior employees already have left for competitors such as Citadel, bu=
t Two Sigma=E2=80=99s results remain strong. There are few signs investors =
are pulling their investments, and the firm is still profitable.
The fund=E2=80=99s managers can=E2=80=99t make any decisions, but it turns =
out that=E2=80=99s for the best.

 =20
   =20
      MiFID II
   =20
 =20

Sell-side stock research has many functions,
  [2]
=C2=A0but the simplest is: It sells stocks. If you are a brokerage firm and=
 you make money by charging customers commissions for trading stocks, you m=
ostly=C2=A0want them to trade more stocks. If you call them up and say =E2=
=80=9Chey, I got a stock, it=E2=80=99s a good one,=E2=80=9D maybe they will=
 buy it. But if you send them research from your specialized stock research=
er, with a detailed financial model and insights on the company=E2=80=99s b=
usiness and a serious-sounding Buy recommendation, they will be more likely=
 to buy it, and from you.
  [3]
 =E2=80=9CWhat great service you are providing,=E2=80=9D they will say, =E2=
=80=9Cgiving us all this free detailed information about the stock.=E2=80=
=9D And you=E2=80=99ll get your commission.
This is not necessarily a product you can=C2=A0charge=C2=A0for.=C2=A0I mean=
, you could. Some investors really value the stuff that sell-side research =
provides =E2=80=94=C2=A0the financial modeling and insights, but also the c=
orporate access and buy-side coordination function =E2=80=94=C2=A0and would=
 pay for it, or some of it, sometimes, for some stocks. But to the extent t=
hat the purpose of sell-side research is to=C2=A0convince customers to do t=
rades,=C2=A0why would the customers pay for it? To the extent that sell-sid=
e research is=C2=A0an advertisement for stock trading, you can=E2=80=99t=C2=
=A0charge=C2=A0for it: You=C2=A0give away=C2=A0the=C2=A0ads, to sell the th=
ing (trading) that makes you money.
  [4]

For various reasons one does not quite=C2=A0talk=C2=A0like this about sell-=
side research, and so it is possible to confuse yourself into a view that i=
s like =E2=80=9Csell-side research is a valuable standalone product that br=
okerages should charge for directly, instead of smuggling its price into tr=
ading commissions.=E2=80=9D If you think like that, you might even identify=
 a conflict of interest: Institutional investment=C2=A0managers=C2=A0benefi=
t from the research (they learn about stocks by reading the research), whil=
e their=C2=A0clients=C2=A0pay for it (the commissions are charged to the cl=
ients=E2=80=99 accounts). Whereas if the brokers charged for the research d=
irectly, the managers would pay for it themselves, making everything fairer=
 and tidier.
And so you might, as the European Union did in its Markets in Financial Ins=
truments Directive, or MiFID II, require brokers to charge separately for r=
esearch. And then it might turn out there=E2=80=99s not much of a market fo=
r that, and you might change your mind. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s   Justina Lee r=
eports:

A piece of European Union legislation that forced financial firms to separa=
te the cost of investment research from that of trading could be reversed u=
nder plans being championed by member states.
In upcoming negotiations with the European Parliament aimed at revising MiF=
ID II =E2=80=94 a set of broader reforms that came into force in 2018 =E2=
=80=94 the states will seek a near total U-turn on the rules behind so-call=
ed unbundling.=C2=A0
Their proposals would mean an investment firm would only have to inform cli=
ents whether they are paying for research and trading jointly, and record t=
he charges attributable to each.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s a dramatic shift from current regulations, which separated t=
he two in a bid to eliminate conflicts of interest that could distract mone=
y managers from seeking the cheapest transaction costs for investors. But e=
vidence suggests research provision across the region has suffered as a res=
ult. =E2=80=A6
Putting an explicit price tag on research resulted in reduced stock coverag=
e, raising concern that the rules are hurting Europe=E2=80=99s financial ma=
rkets =E2=80=94 especially its small-caps.=C2=A0
In response, the European Commission =E2=80=94 the EU=E2=80=99s executive b=
ody =E2=80=94 in December suggested a partial easing of the rules surroundi=
ng research. But the published stance of the Council of the European Union,=
 which represents member states, goes much further.
=E2=80=9CThe research unbundling rules need to be further adjusted to offer=
 the investment firms more flexibility=E2=80=9D in order to ensure sufficie=
nt coverage especially of small- and mid-caps, according to the group=E2=80=
=99s mandate for negotiations. =E2=80=9CThis would however require to maint=
ain a necessary transparency vis-a-vis the client.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

If you are sending a customer a lot of research reports about small-cap sto=
cks, it is generally not because the customer is desperate to learn more ab=
out small-cap stocks and will pay you thousands of dollars for your insight=
s. It is because you want the customer to learn more about small-cap stocks=
, so she=E2=80=99ll buy some.

 =20
   =20
      Crypto.com prop desk
   =20
 =20

The way   the US stock market works is:
=09A retail broker (Robinhood, Fidelity, etc.) has a website, where you can=
 put in an order to sell stock.=09They send the order to a market maker (Ci=
tadel Securities, Virtu, Jane Street, etc.)=C2=A0who buys the stock from yo=
u.=09The market maker goes to a stock exchange (the New York Stock Exchange=
,=C2=A0Nasdaq, etc.) to sell the stock to another market maker or to an ins=
titutional investor.

This is not exactly right,
  [5]
=C2=A0but it is a good rough intuition. Trading with retail customers is lu=
crative, and somebody who operates a retail-customer-facing website will wa=
nt to monetize that fact; in the US stock market, that means selling the re=
tail order flow to a market maker. Meanwhile there are public stock exchang=
es where institutions and market makers can trade with each other.
The way the crypto market often works is the same except:
=09A crypto exchange operates the website for retail customers, and the exc=
hange for market makers and institutional investors.=09Also it often quietl=
y operates the market maker who trades with the retail customers.

The  Financial Times reports:

Crypto.com, the exchange endorsed by Hollywood actor Matt Damon, deploys in=
ternal teams to trade tokens for profit, the latest sign of potential confl=
icts of interest in the digital assets industry.
The Singapore-based group, one of the top-10 crypto marketplaces in the wor=
ld, operates proprietary trading and market making teams, according to five=
 people with direct knowledge of the matter. =E2=80=A6
One of the people with direct knowledge about the teams said that Crypto.co=
m executives gave other, external trading houses =E2=80=9Cabsolutely dramat=
ic sworn statements that Crypto.com was in no way involved in trading=E2=80=
=9D, while another said that employees were asked to =E2=80=9Csay there is =
no internal market maker type operation=E2=80=9D.
In response to questions from the Financial Times, Crypto.com said that emp=
loyees had not been asked to lie to other market participants.
Crypto.com said: =E2=80=9CWe have an internal market maker that operates on=
 the Crypto.com exchange and that internal market maker is treated exactly =
the same as third-party market makers that identically facilitate tight spr=
eads and efficient markets on our platform.=E2=80=9D
=E2=80=9CThis is not a controversial practice,=E2=80=9D the company added.
The company said that most of its revenues came from its app for retail tra=
ders where Crypto.com was the customers=E2=80=99 counterparty for transacti=
ons and which it ran as a broker model. =E2=80=9CAs such, the Crypto.com tr=
ading team ensures that Crypto.com is risk neutral by hedging these positio=
ns on a number of venues, including the Crypto.com exchange,=E2=80=9D the c=
ompany added.
Its exchange is for institutional traders and =E2=80=9Coperates as a level =
playing field trading venue=E2=80=9D, the company said.

That might cover various things =E2=80=94=C2=A0the internal trading team mi=
ght do proprietary directional trading and/or institutional market making o=
n the exchange =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I read it to say=C2=A0mostly =E2=80=9Cfac=
ing Crypto.com=E2=80=99s retail customers is lucrative, so Crypto.com does =
that itself, and when it trades with those customers it ends up with=C2=A0p=
ositions that it has to lay off on the institutional exchange.=E2=80=9D Tha=
t=E2=80=99s kind of how the stock market works except that in stocks the re=
tail broker, the market maker and the exchange are three separate entities.=
 In crypto they are all the same.

