     =20
Fourteenth Law of Insider Trading
   =20
 =20

On Friday   I proposed an Eleventh Law of Insider Trading, =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=
=80=99t insider trade while drunk.=E2=80=9D I need to make a few correction=
s and clarifications to this law.
First, and most important: I mean, I used to have a schtick of announcing =
=E2=80=9Claws of insider trading,=E2=80=9D which are never legal advice; wh=
en I got to 10 in 2018 I  did a little commemorative post. But then I=C2=A0=
got a little bored, and it has been so long since I announced a new law of =
insider trading that I forgot some. Here are the actual Eleventh, Twelfth a=
nd Thirteenth Laws, in their order of promulgation:
11. =E2=80=9CIf you=C2=A0are=C2=A0planning to insider trade, probably don=
=E2=80=99t keep a Google Doc spreadsheet of the Money Stuff Laws of Insider=
 Trading.=E2=80=9D (This was actually in my  little commemorative post.)
12. =E2=80=9CIf you insider trade by buying short-dated out-of-the-money ca=
ll options on a merger target, and the SEC freezes your profits,   don=E2=
=80=99t show up in a U.S. court to ask for them back.=E2=80=9D (There are  =
 exceptions.)
13. =E2=80=9CIf you are going to insider trade, or commit securities fraud =
generally,   don=E2=80=99t talk loudly about it on the Acela from Washingto=
n to New York.=E2=80=9D
So =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t insider trade drunk=E2=80=9D is actually the Four=
teenth Law of Insider Trading, sorry sorry sorry. Unless I=E2=80=99m missin=
g another one. I need a better system to track them. (Here is  a Github, no=
t maintained by me,=C2=A0but it is also missing some late entrants.) Anyway=
 the important point here is that none of this is legal advice.
Second, speaking of =E2=80=9Cnot legal advice,=E2=80=9D this weekend  Steph=
en Bainbridge considered this case and concluded that =E2=80=9Cvoluntary in=
toxication might well be a viable defense to an insider trading charge=E2=
=80=9D: To convict you of the crime of insider trading, prosecutors need to=
 prove that you traded with some intention to defraud, and if you were drun=
k enough perhaps they will be unable to prove that=C2=A0intent. This sugges=
ts the possibility of an Alternate Fourteenth Law of Insider Trading: =E2=
=80=9COnly=C2=A0insider trade while drunk.=E2=80=9D
A reader pointed out that someone=C2=A0did=C2=A0try this defense in Hong Ko=
ng in 2012. A=C2=A0non-executive director of=C2=A0Hong Kong Aircraft Engine=
ering Co. was charged with=C2=A0insider dealing: A merger proposal came in,=
 the=C2=A0chief executive officer called the director to invite him to a bo=
ard meeting to discuss the deal,=C2=A0he went to=C2=A0lunch and bought 4,00=
0 shares of the company=E2=80=99s stock. The director, =E2=80=9Cwho pleaded=
 not guilty at trial, claimed that at the time he purchased the shares, he =
had forgotten he was an independent non-executive director of HAECO; he was=
 intoxicated and that he did not intend to profit from his trading.=E2=80=
=9D This defense did not work =E2=80=94=C2=A0he was convicted =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0though the Securities and Futures Commission did note that he =E2=80=9Cc=
laimed that he had drunk a gin and tonic followed by two glasses of white w=
ine and two glasses of red wine over a four-course lunch at the Hong Kong C=
lub.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

