  [1] Old enough that *arguably* 2004-2006 was the first real interest-rate=
-hiking cycle of my professional life, but I was a baby lawyer then so I am=
 not going to count it.


  [2] We have talked a lot around here about the   corporate-access functio=
ns of sell-side analysts. And last week  Byrne Hobart wrote about =E2=80=9C=
What Does an =E2=80=98Analyst=E2=80=99 Do,=E2=80=9D with a focus on the way=
s in which sell-side analysts coordinate the views of buy-side investors: =
=E2=80=9CPart of a sell-side analyst's job is to articulate different flavo=
rs of the current buy-side consensus. =E2=80=A6 So buy-side analysts talk t=
o sell-side analysts partly because other buy-side analysts do; research qu=
ality ends up being a Schelling Point for arranging even higher-quality dis=
cussions with opinionated, well-informed people on either side of the argum=
ent. So the end goal of a sell-side analyst publishing a good report is not=
 just to get opinions out there, but to solicit other opinions, synthesize =
them, and hopefully get to the right answer. =E2=80=A6 Markets thrive at a =
controlled level of information asymmetry: if everyone agrees on everything=
, there's no reason to trade. If nobody agrees on anything, the spread betw=
een buyers and sellers is too high and there's no liquidity. The function o=
f sell-side analysts is to smooth the flow of information, to articulate wh=
at the relevant views are, and to connect people, directly or indirectly, w=
ith other people who will change their minds.=E2=80=9D


  [3] [If you send them a report with a Sell recommendation, maybe they wil=
l sell it? This is, however, a pretty advanced move.


  [4] This is a stylized model, and probably overstates the value of the co=
mmissions. Dan Davies wrote last month: "Sellside research is to a very sma=
ll extent advertisement for brokerage services (which are barely profitable=
 themselves these days), and mainly a way to build the kind of buddy networ=
ks with companies and investors that are essential if you want to do adviso=
ry or have a capital markets business. It=E2=80=99s noticeable that Deutsch=
e Bank still has an equity research department even though it doesn=E2=80=
=99t have an equity trading department, and that it appears to have acquire=
d Numis for its network of UK corporate brokerage relationships (of which t=
he provision of research coverage is an important part)." The research is n=
ot so much an advertisement for "trade this stock today" as it is for "trus=
t us for your complex financial services needs." It is a relationship-build=
ing calling card rather than a product sold on its own.=20


  [5] In particular, the market maker would probably prefer to sell your st=
ock to another customer of the retail broker, rather than offloading it on =
the public exchange.


