<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Rates go up</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is maybe the first real interest-rate-hik=
ing cycle of my professional life, and I=E2=80=99m kind of excited? Not jus=
t <em>my=C2=A0</em>professional life. I=E2=80=99m pretty old!<a class=3D"fo=
otnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !import=
ant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0A whole lot of people in fairly senior roles at a whole lot of fi=
nancial services companies grew up=C2=A0a world of low interest rates; larg=
e expanses of the financial industry=C2=A0collectively forgot that rates co=
uld go up. Now rates have gone up. Those two facts =E2=80=94=C2=A0rates hav=
e gone up, and lots of people have=C2=A0never seen rates go up =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0are going to lead to interesting results. Weird stuff will happen becaus=
e the most predictable fact in the world =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cinterest r=
ates can=E2=80=99t stay low forever=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0was, somehow, u=
nforeseen.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Look around! Is the story of crypto =E2=80=9Cw=
hen rates were zero for ages, a dollar in 100 years was worth as much as a =
dollar now, so people got really into trading digital assets that had no fo=
reseeable cash flows, and then rates went up and everyone woke up and reali=
zed that was dumb and stopped=E2=80=9D? Is that also the story of blitzscal=
ing tech-startup unicorns? No, but also a little bit yes?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More concretely, is the story of the 2023 US r=
egional banking crisis =E2=80=9Cwhen rates were zero forever, banks borrowe=
d short at 0% to lend long at 3%, and then rates went up, their asset value=
s collapsed and there was a run on deposits, all of which was extremely for=
eseeable except that the banks and bank regulators forgot that interest rat=
es could go up?=E2=80=9D I mean, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/31848390.258405/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDQvbm9ib2R5LXRydXN0cy10aGUtYmFua3Mtbm93P2NtcGlkPUJ=
CRDA2MjAyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dG=
VyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDYyMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cBe822e1e9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">  I have argued</a> that the actual story is <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31848390.258405/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMjIvYmFua3MtZ2=
90LXJpc2luZy1yYXRlcy13cm9uZz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjIwMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVka=
XVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA2MjAmdXRtX2NhbXBh=
aWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB91f843ce" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  more subtl=
e</a> than that, that you need to think about things like unexpectedly high=
 deposit betas and declining relationships and=C2=A0broader public awarenes=
s of=C2=A0bank balance sheets,=C2=A0that banks reasonably expected rising r=
ates to be=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>for them and were caught out by social a=
nd technological changes. But that=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>kind of a straight=
forward explanation, no? =E2=80=9CSome banks were not prepared for rising r=
ates because they forgot that there was such a thing=E2=80=9D?=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or I mean =E2=80=A6=C2=A0is the story of moder=
n private equity and leveraged-loan markets something like =E2=80=9Cfloatin=
g-rate debt is very cheap when rates are zero, so if you buy a bunch of com=
panies and load them up with cheap floating-rate debt then you will predict=
ably have high returns to equity and manageable interest expense,=E2=80=9D =
and then rates went up and the whole thing broke? Do we have an economy in =
which a lot of businesses are financed with a lot of floating-rate debt, no=
t because that is a sensible way to finance their businesses in the long ru=
n, but because a lot of fairly young private-equity professionals forgot th=
at rates could go up? Ehh I don=E2=80=99t know, not really, but maybe a lit=
tle. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/31848390.258405/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGl=
jbGVzLzIwMjMtMDYtMjAvcHJpdmF0ZS1lcXVpdHktZmlybXMtZXhwb3NlZC1ieS11bmhlZGdlZC=
1yaXNrLWludGVyZXN0LXJhdGVzLXN1cmdlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MjAyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0b=
V9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDYyMCZ1dG1f=
Y2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB93060d59" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Sil=
as Brown, Abhinav Ramnarayan and Paula Seligson report</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By failing to appreciate just how much central=
 banks would jack up rates, many private equity firms opted against hedging=
 arrangements that could have shielded companies saddled with $3 trillion i=
n floating-rate debt from rising interest costs, that in some cases, double=
d or more. For much of the past decade, those hedges cost next to nothing.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CNot many folks were worrying about th=
is and a lot of businesses have been burnt really badly,=E2=80=9D said Chri=
s Scott, Carlyle Group Inc.=E2=80=99s head of European capital markets.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Estimates are hotly debated and buyout firms a=
cross the industry declined to talk specifics. But in the US, nearly three-=
quarters of the floating-rate debt taken out during the leveraged-buyout bo=
om lacked hedges as recently as August, according to an analysis by Bank of=
 America. Man Group Plc research suggests that over 70% of the total in Eur=
ope remained unhedged at the end of January, well after the European Centra=
l Bank began its tightening campaign.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Whatever the precise number, this much is clea=
r: The consequences of rising rates for hundreds, if not thousands, of comp=
anies could be crippling, and the fallout widespread. Not only for investor=
s, who face deep losses, or workers, who stand to lose jobs, but also the g=
lobal economy, which could be upended if corporate defaults pile up. =E2=80=
=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The situation is the latest example of how Wal=
l Street=E2=80=99s best and the brightest =E2=80=94 from bank executives to=
 traders and economists =E2=80=94 were almost uniformly blindsided by the p=
ickup in inflation and how forcefully central banks around the world would =
respond to tamp it down. It=E2=80=99s also a sharp reversal for private equ=
ity itself, which leveraged a flood of central bank money to finance a reco=
rd number of buyouts at rock-bottom rates over the past decade. =E2=80=A6</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Across North America, interest costs at the me=
dian private equity-backed company ballooned to 43% of Ebitda last year, ac=
cording to research published last month by Verdad Advisers, which analyzed=
 350 such companies that are either publicly traded or have publicly traded=
 debt. Not only is that six times as much as the median S&amp;P 500 company=
, but the interest burden will keep growing this year as rates keep rising.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In fact, interest rates on the largest US leve=
raged loans (which simply refer to junk-rated loans which are often used to=
 finance buyouts) hit an average of 10% this month, from 3.9% at the end of=
 2021, just before the Federal Reserve embarked on its most aggressive tigh=
tening campaign in a generation, based on the Morningstar LSTA US Leveraged=
 Loan 100 Index.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At some level =E2=80=9Cas interest rates go up=
, companies will have to pay more interest on their debt=E2=80=9D is a pret=
ty banal finding, and yet it does seem to come as a surprise.</p>
