<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sell-side stock research has many functions,<a=
 class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpa=
rent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0but the simplest is: It sells stocks. If you are a brokerage firm=
 and you make money by charging customers commissions for trading stocks, y=
ou mostly=C2=A0want them to trade more stocks. If you call them up and say =
=E2=80=9Chey, I got a stock, it=E2=80=99s a good one,=E2=80=9D maybe they w=
ill buy it. But if you send them research from your specialized stock resea=
rcher, with a detailed financial model and insights on the company=E2=80=99=
s business and a serious-sounding Buy recommendation, they will be more lik=
ely to buy it, and from you.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !import=
ant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> =E2=80=9CWhat great service you are providing,=E2=80=9D they will say,=
 =E2=80=9Cgiving us all this free detailed information about the stock.=E2=
=80=9D And you=E2=80=99ll get your commission.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not necessarily a product you can=C2=
=A0<em>charge=C2=A0</em>for.=C2=A0I mean, you could. Some investors really =
value the stuff that sell-side research provides =E2=80=94=C2=A0the financi=
al modeling and insights, but also the corporate access and buy-side coordi=
nation function =E2=80=94=C2=A0and would pay for it, or some of it, sometim=
es, for some stocks. But to the extent that the purpose of sell-side resear=
ch is to=C2=A0<em>convince customers to do trades,=C2=A0</em>why would the =
customers pay for it? To the extent that sell-side research is=C2=A0<em>an =
advertisement for stock trading</em>, you can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>charge=C2=
=A0</em>for it: You=C2=A0give away<em>=C2=A0</em>the=C2=A0<em>ads</em>, to =
sell the thing (trading) that makes you money.<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For various reasons one does not quite=C2=A0<e=
m>talk=C2=A0</em>like this about sell-side research, and so it is possible =
to confuse yourself into a view that is like =E2=80=9Csell-side research is=
 a valuable standalone product that brokerages should charge for directly, =
instead of smuggling its price into trading commissions.=E2=80=9D If you th=
ink like that, you might even identify a conflict of interest: Institutiona=
l investment=C2=A0<em>managers=C2=A0</em>benefit from the research (they le=
arn about stocks by reading the research), while their=C2=A0<em>clients=C2=
=A0</em>pay for it (the commissions are charged to the clients=E2=80=99 acc=
ounts). Whereas if the brokers charged for the research directly, the manag=
ers would pay for it themselves, making everything fairer and tidier.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so you might, as the European Union did in=
 its Markets in Financial Instruments Directive, or MiFID II, require broke=
rs to charge separately for research. And then it might turn out there=E2=
=80=99s not much of a market for that, and you might change your mind. Bloo=
mberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31=
848390.258405/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtM=
DYtMjAvbWlmaWQtcmV2YW1wLWNvdWxkLXJldmVyc2UtYmFuLW9uLWJ1bmRsaW5nLXJlc2VhcmNo=
LXdpdGgtdHJhZGluZz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjIwMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWl=
sJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA2MjAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbm=
V5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9053b975" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Justina Lee reports<=
/a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A piece of European Union legislation that for=
ced financial firms to separate the cost of investment research from that o=
f trading could be reversed under plans being championed by member states.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In upcoming negotiations with the European Par=
liament aimed at revising MiFID II =E2=80=94 a set of broader reforms that =
came into force in 2018 =E2=80=94 the states will seek a near total U-turn =
on the rules behind so-called unbundling.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Their proposals would mean an investment firm =
would only have to inform clients whether they are paying for research and =
trading jointly, and record the charges attributable to each.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s a dramatic shift from current r=
egulations, which separated the two in a bid to eliminate conflicts of inte=
rest that could distract money managers from seeking the cheapest transacti=
on costs for investors. But evidence suggests research provision across the=
 region has suffered as a result. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Putting an explicit price tag on research resu=
lted in reduced stock coverage, raising concern that the rules are hurting =
Europe=E2=80=99s financial markets =E2=80=94 especially its small-caps.=C2=
=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In response, the European Commission =E2=80=94=
 the EU=E2=80=99s executive body =E2=80=94 in December suggested a partial =
easing of the rules surrounding research. But the published stance of the C=
ouncil of the European Union, which represents member states, goes much fur=
ther.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe research unbundling rules need to=
 be further adjusted to offer the investment firms more flexibility=E2=80=
=9D in order to ensure sufficient coverage especially of small- and mid-cap=
s, according to the group=E2=80=99s mandate for negotiations. =E2=80=9CThis=
 would however require to maintain a necessary transparency vis-a-vis the c=
lient.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are sending a customer a lot of researc=
h reports about small-cap stocks, it is generally not because the customer =
is desperate to learn more about small-cap stocks and will pay you thousand=
s of dollars for your insights. It is because <em>you</em> want the custome=
r to learn more about small-cap stocks, so she=E2=80=99ll buy some.</p>
