<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/31848390.258405/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlu=
aW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDUvcm9iaW5ob29kLWdhbWVzdG9wLXNhZ2EtcHJlc3N1cmV=
zLXBheW1lbnQtZm9yLW9yZGVyLWZsb3c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYyMDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX2=
1lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNjIwJnV0bV9jY=
W1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB168b9724" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  the US=
 stock market works</a> is:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A retail broker (Robinhood, Fidelity, =
etc.) has a website, where you can put in an order to sell stock.</li>=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They send the order to a market maker (Cita=
del Securities, Virtu, Jane Street, etc.)=C2=A0who buys the stock from you.=
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The market maker goes to a stock =
exchange (the New York Stock Exchange,=C2=A0Nasdaq, etc.) to sell the stock=
 to another market maker or to an institutional investor.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not exactly right,<a class=3D"footnote=
-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; d=
isplay: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0but it is a good rough intuition. Trading with retail customers i=
s lucrative, and somebody who operates a retail-customer-facing website wil=
l want to monetize that fact; in the US stock market, that means selling th=
e retail order flow to a market maker. Meanwhile there are public stock exc=
hanges where institutions and market makers can trade with each other.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way the crypto market often works is the s=
ame except:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A crypto exchange operates the website=
 for retail customers, <em>and</em> the exchange for market makers and inst=
itutional investors.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Also it often=
 quietly operates the market maker who trades with the retail customers.</l=
i>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/31848390.258405/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvYjVkMmJm=
NGItMjI1Yy00ZjMwLTlmMWMtY2JlOGRjNzYyZmE4/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbe60e5c6"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;"> Financial Times reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Crypto.com, the exchange endorsed by Hollywood=
 actor Matt Damon, deploys internal teams to trade tokens for profit, the l=
atest sign of potential conflicts of interest in the digital assets industr=
y.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Singapore-based group, one of the top-10 c=
rypto marketplaces in the world, operates proprietary trading and market ma=
king teams, according to five people with direct knowledge of the matter. =
=E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One of the people with direct knowledge about =
the teams said that Crypto.com executives gave other, external trading hous=
es =E2=80=9Cabsolutely dramatic sworn statements that Crypto.com was in no =
way involved in trading=E2=80=9D, while another said that employees were as=
ked to =E2=80=9Csay there is no internal market maker type operation=E2=80=
=9D.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In response to questions from the Financial Ti=
mes, Crypto.com said that employees had not been asked to lie to other mark=
et participants.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Crypto.com said: =E2=80=9CWe have an internal =
market maker that operates on the Crypto.com exchange and that internal mar=
ket maker is treated exactly the same as third-party market makers that ide=
ntically facilitate tight spreads and efficient markets on our platform.=E2=
=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThis is not a controversial practice,=
=E2=80=9D the company added.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The company said that most of its revenues cam=
e from its app for retail traders where Crypto.com was the customers=E2=80=
=99 counterparty for transactions and which it ran as a broker model. =E2=
=80=9CAs such, the Crypto.com trading team ensures that Crypto.com is risk =
neutral by hedging these positions on a number of venues, including the Cry=
pto.com exchange,=E2=80=9D the company added.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Its exchange is for institutional traders and =
=E2=80=9Coperates as a level playing field trading venue=E2=80=9D, the comp=
any said.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That might cover various things =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the internal trading team might do proprietary directional trading and/o=
r institutional market making on the exchange =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I read it =
to say=C2=A0<em>mostly </em>=E2=80=9Cfacing Crypto.com=E2=80=99s retail cus=
tomers is lucrative, so Crypto.com does that itself, and when it trades wit=
h those customers it ends up with=C2=A0positions that it has to lay off on =
the institutional exchange.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s kind of how the stock m=
arket works except that in stocks the retail broker, the market maker and t=
he exchange are three separate entities. In crypto they are all the same.</=
p>
